text: hi everyone
Anthony Fantino here the Internet's
sweatiest music nerd and it's time for a
review own ad songs
ohm is a duo that has been exploring the
darker and the slower side of rock and
metal music for about five studio albums
now including this one and the duo
originally formed after the seminal
stoner and doom metal band sleep had
disbanded the bassist and the drummer
got together made ohm while Matt Pike
guitar player and singer kind of went
off and did high on fire
I will admit I am much more of a high on
fire guy and I'm not saying that you
have to like either ohm or high on fire
but when it comes to rock music that
takes a more meditative approach ohm is
easily one of my least favorite groups
period but the thing is almost every
album that own puts out displeases me
for pretty much the same exact reasons
for one Alf Cisneros vocals whose name
I'm probably butchering to death but his
vocals to me are just really
underwhelming amateur just uninteresting
and the bass lines that he plays to are
pretty forgettable but I keep giving own
a try whenever they put out a new LP
because I love this style of music and
their fans are really passionate about
what they do
plus they have continuously worked with
Steve Albini to produce their records
another guy I have an immense respect
for and I don't think he would continue
working with ohm if he didn't really
love what they were doing now in the
link 2000s the band had kind of a lineup
change and I got excited to see where
they would take their next album the duo
now featured an owl on bass and vocals
and ml a Moe's drummer for the band
Grails and the first LP they made
together I didn't love it but I could
definitely see an improvement
therefore sure the drums were a lot more
detailed and Emmel as well as the guest
musicians on this LP helped bring out
those world music influences that always
seem to be ever so subtly kind of
influencing ohm's vibe on god is good
you had a lot of flutes cellos Tambora
drones the band was really expanding
their sonic palette and it made me
appreciate the hypnotic approach that
they took the music so much more the
vocals still were not really doing much
for me
the bass lines to me were still pretty
mad but the extra instrumentation was
well placed the production was good and
listening to own jam for 10 or more
minutes was sounding pretty good at this
point
and with this new LP ohm basically looks
to continue expanding those
international flavours in their music
you have these Arabic melodies coming
through on hello you have chance and
just droning and repetitive bass lines
contributing again to that hypnotic feel
that always shoots for and another man
whose name I'm about to butcher Robert
ie key Aubrey Lowe who was on owns last
LP just doing extra instrumentation is
now on this album as a full-time member
and he again is bringing that additional
percussion the keys
those Tambora drones has definitely
progressed past their last LP I admire
that they don't want to keep putting out
the same album over and over and over
but there are still things that seem to
kind of be in the band's foundation that
continue to bug me on this album
owls vocals I really don't see the point
in singing this way it just seems so
campy it just seems so fake and just
unappealing it really takes me out of
the vibe of the music the bass lines to
me are still pretty unimaginative but
for the most part the bass the tone of
the bass is great except on the second
track where you do get some distortion
on the bass and for some reason whatever
distortion pedal they're using the low
end of the bass gets totally cut out
it's really muddy
a distortion that doesn't sound good at
all but aside from just the the lack of
adventurous instrumentation though the
instrumentation does sound good and is
well produced the final nail in the
coffin for this album for me is that the
vibe of all of it is very very weak they
certainly try you know the opening track
on here is decked out with a guest
female vocalist singing these chants in
a different language you've got that
extra hand percussion too but the entire
song just feels like it is trying to get
by on the Kitsch of sounding like it's
coming from another country not really
being all that interesting musically
itself when Gorm's isn't giving me
vocals I don't like or bass lines that
I'm never going to remember they're just
kind of creating this character of this
music from another culture in this
really long form Jam style delivery that
I would like a lot more if if those
things were kind of remedied so I'm
really on the fence with this LP and
continue to be with with all of ohms
catalog I didn't really hear anything
that is horrible on this album but I
can't really find anything to celebrate
either I'm really feeling like a strong
five to a light six on this album what
